He recognized that an extensive Federal government would be expensive and potentially tyrannical. However, he also believed that a simple, literal interpretation was inadequate, as it could lead to corruption without considering the intent of the founders. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly described the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking at the data shown in Figure 17, it's clear that there was a significant drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. At first glance, this was a bit of a letdown, and it's tough to pinpoint the reason behind it. With the onset of winter on a New England campus, it's likely that the decrease in bike and foot traffic played a part in the decline. Additionally, December marks the end of the fall semester, a time when students are busy wrapping up schoolwork and dealing with final exams, which might have caused the commuter log to fall off many people's radar. The holiday season also kicked in during this time, followed by a month-long break for students and faculty, which probably contributed to the low numbers. Even when classes resumed in late January, submissions remained low, raising the question of whether this was a temporary lull or a sign of a more permanent drop in engagement. One possibility is that any project of this nature tends to have an initial surge of enthusiasm, followed by a gradual decline. To combat this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign aimed at reviving the initiative, which successfully resulted in an uptick in log submissions for that month. However, this still left us wondering how to maintain momentum in the face of the inevitable dip in engagement that occurs when students and faculty are on break. 

Another challenge that came up during this project (and one that's likely to arise in any alternative commuting initiative) is the fact that driving a car gives people a sense of freedom and independence that's deeply ingrained in our culture. To overcome this, we offered incentives in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, and other establishments. It would have been interesting to see how bigger prizes, such as a new bike or a hybrid/electric car, might have impacted participation. Perhaps if we had announced these larger prizes in December and January, that might have helped to mitigate the dip in engagement that we experienced. The value of the prizes didn't change over the course of the project, but if we had upped the ante, it's possible that participation would have remained strong rather than dipping.

In the world of investing, Exchange-Traded Funds (ETFs) have gained popularity due to their unique combination of characteristics - flexibility, diversification, and low expense ratios. An ETF is essentially a security that tracks an index, commodity, or a basket of assets, similar to an index fund, but trades on an exchange like a stock. This enables investors to reap the benefits of single stock ownership, such as short-selling, buying on margin, and purchasing as few as one share in a transaction. Furthermore, ETFs offer a wider variety of funds to choose from, making it easier for investors to find the right fit for their investment goals.

However, as with any investment, there are some downsides to consider. For instance, ETFs come with a commission on trades, similar to buying or selling stocks. Despite these minor drawbacks, the benefits of ETFs are undeniable. In this analysis, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it to its top 10 holdings to determine whether owning a single ETF is equivalent to a diversified portfolio of the individual stocks. We will also investigate whether a reconfigured portfolio of the same stocks could provide a better return and lower beta.

For the sake of simplicity, we have chosen to focus on the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Below is a list of the top 10 holdings and their corresponding percentage of total assets.

To gauge the effectiveness of these 10 stocks in representing the ETF as a whole, we will calculate their contributions to a portfolio's beta and return if the portfolio were made up entirely of these stocks in the proportions determined by the ETF's holdings. The calculations are included in the chart below.

The chart clearly shows that a portfolio consisting only of the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. Moreover, the beta of this portfolio is 0.12 lower than that of the ETF. Based on these results, it appears that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta. Nevertheless, it's essential to verify whether these differences are statistically significant.

To determine this, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

It's interesting to note that Edgar Allan Poe considered "Dream-Land" one of his standout poems. In this poem, Poe uses the term "Thulé" twice, which is a reference to a mysterious island located north of Britain, viewed by the Greeks as the edge of the world. However, Virgil is not the only source for this term, as some scholars suggest that Poe may have been influenced by German literature. Poe was indeed a fan of German authors, including Goethe. 

In fact, a closer look at Goethe's work "Faust" reveals a poem called "The King of Thulé." This poem tells the story of a king who is heartbroken after his wife's passing, and he turns to excessive drinking. The poem's themes of loss and despair are eerily similar to those found in "Dream-Land." It's possible that Poe was paying homage to Goethe's work, as scholar Karl J. Arndt notes in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon." Furthermore, Goethe's "Faust" was a celebrated work of poetic drama, published in two parts in 1808 and 1832, respectively. The parallels between "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" are striking, with both works exploring themes of loss, grief, and the human condition.

Poe's use of the term "Thulé" in his collected writings is notable, with references in both "The Pit and the Pendulum" and "Dream-Land." The two poems can be seen as companion pieces, with "The King of Thulé" serving as a dark reflection of the themes found in "Dream-Land." In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a desolate landscape, haunted by the memories of loved ones, while in "The King of Thulé," Goethe's king is similarly consumed by grief after the loss of his wife.

Given Poe's admiration for Tennyson and his familiarity with German literature, it's likely that he would have been aware of Goethe's work. In fact, Poe's respect for Tennyson suggests that he would have been exposed to Goethe's writings through various reproductions and translations that were popular at the time.

In a recent court case, a woman named Jennifer Palmer is suing D&D Markets for punitive damages after she slipped and fell on an applesauce spill at the store. The store manager, Paul Martin, was informed about the spill not once, but twice, and chose to ignore it for 30 minutes because he was eating dinner. The question is whether Martin's actions were malicious enough to warrant punitive damages under California law. 

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Palmer's claim outright. To win punitive damages, she'll need to show that Martin's actions were done with a reckless disregard for the harm they would cause. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known about the dangers of leaving a spill unattended, given that several customers had slipped and fallen due to similar incidents at the store in the past. However, it's less clear whether Martin's actions were truly malicious, given that he had been warned twice about the spill. Still, Palmer has a strong argument that Martin failed to act with the necessary care to ensure customer safety, especially given the six slip-and-fall incidents at the store in 2009.

According to court records, on October 13, 2009, two employees, Rich Wayne and Mary J. Haddigan, separately informed Martin about the applesauce spill, but he dismissed their concerns, saying he was busy eating dinner. Thirty minutes later, Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, severely injuring her back. Prior to her accident, five other customers had reported slipping and falling at the store that year.

Under California law, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." The law defines malice as conduct that was intended to cause harm or was done with a "despicable" disregard for others' safety. The court has ruled that conduct is malicious when the defendant is aware of the likely harm their actions will cause and deliberately chooses to ignore it. In this case, Palmer may have a strong case for punitive damages, but it will ultimately depend on how the court interprets Martin's actions and intentions.

It's been almost four years since I took an Islam course at CBC, and one topic continues to fascinate me to this day: whether Islam is inherently a hostile religion. In my opinion, this question is more relevant now than ever, especially considering the shift in media portrayals of Islam and its adherents since 9/11. It's intriguing to think about the possibility of a presidential candidate with a strong Muslim background, like Barack Obama, running for office in 2001. 

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad has always piqued my interest. The more I learn about Muhammad's life, the more I'm struck by the contrast between the historical figure and the depiction in his biography. I previously believed that Muhammad forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and imposing his religion on them. However, the biography presents a different narrative – one of a humble and self-effacing figure who was misunderstood and humbled himself to others. It was only after people witnessed his teachings that they came to see the truth in them. 

What's even more striking is the similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' attributed to Muhammad. For instance, the story of multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men is a notable example. The way this story is told makes me think that the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as a prophet who didn't need to prove anything, but simply lived in truth and performed miracles. This approach, however, undermines the significance of Jesus' life and teachings. It's as if they're attempting to steal and co-opt the essence of Jesus' message through Muhammad. 

Another aspect of the biography that raises questions is the way it presents stories of people converting to Islam. While the authors aim to demonstrate the truth of these stories, the fact that they're often based on second-hand accounts from multiple people makes me skeptical. I think this approach diminishes the impact of the stories and makes them seem suspicious. 

What bothers me most is the way the biography portrays Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man. However, historical accounts contradict this image, and I'm left wondering if modern Muslims are aware of the true circumstances surrounding Muhammad's rise to power.

The core teachings of Jesus and the original beliefs he held during his lifetime were quickly abandoned as Christianity evolved after his passing.  If we look at this historical trend in broad strokes, it appears that Christianity has been moving further and further away from its roots over time.  However, there is an increasing awareness and a progressive movement in today's world that could potentially alter this trajectory.  While traditionalists may resist any ideas that diverge from their established beliefs, they might not be influential enough to dictate the future of the faith.  As time progresses, Christians will increasingly become aware of the history of their faith and crave a closer understanding of the original intentions of Jesus' teachings.  It may take several decades or even centuries, but it's inevitable that we will see a major shift in the course of Christian history, resulting in a return to the faith's original form.  A movement will emerge that will systematically peel away the layers of doctrine that have been added over time, effectively reversing the clock and returning to the core principles that Jesus introduced to humanity in the name of God.  When this trend gains momentum in the United States and Europe, it will spread across the masses, prompting a return to the simplicity of following Jesus' ideas as they were intended, rather than the complex interpretations that have developed over time.  The church will continue to serve as a guiding institution, but its influence will be characterized by a growing uniformity of belief and practice.  Rather than differences between regions, denominations, and divisions, we can expect to see increasing similarities.  History has shown us that great reversals can occur, such as the transformation of the Roman Empire from a persecutor of Christians to a Christian institution.  Similarly, our nation has progressed from African-American slavery to African-American leadership.  The impending reversal in the Christian faith will be a significant event that will undo the accumulated complexities of history and seek out the faith's original source, resulting in a unification of the diverse branches of Christianity.  A crucial factor in making this process possible will be the shift from interpreting Jesus' words as literal statements to understanding them as metaphors.  So what led to the transformation of Christianity over time?

Looking back into history, we find that the seeds of the Christian faith were planted in Judaism, the theological foundation of the Christian religion.  By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., the core elements of monotheism, divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were already in place.  However, the Jewish population was not a unified entity, with various groups, such as the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people, each with their own distinct spirit and perspective.

I firmly believe that The Jungle portrays the darker aspects of human nature, exposing people's inherent selfishness and self-centeredness. Deep down, many individuals are primarily concerned with their own well-being and success, often disregarding the needs and welfare of those around them. The novel masterfully illustrates this concept through the actions of the factory owners and managers. Their sole focus is on expanding their businesses and increasing their wealth, without any regard for the consequences or harm caused to others. As Upton Sinclair so vividly describes, the factory's towering structures and smoke-belching chimneys symbolize the devastating impact of their greed. The pollution and unsanitary conditions surrounding Packingtown are a stark reminder of the owners' disregard for human and animal life.

Moreover, the owners and managers showed a blatant disregard for their employees, whom they exploited for their own gain. They would stop at nothing to save a buck, even if it meant subjecting their workers to inhumane conditions and long working hours. The novel starkly highlights the lack of empathy and decency in the workplace, where a worker's value was measured solely by their productivity, not their human worth. The absence of labor regulations and worker protections during that era allowed the factory owners to operate with impunity, forcing their employees to endure grueling conditions and live in squalor. Although the novel doesn't explicitly state it, the workers who toiled and suffered in Packingtown were essentially treated like slaves, with no access to resources, information, or support. Even the unions that formed to protect workers often ended up taking advantage of them, further exacerbating their struggles.

The novel paints a grim picture of a system where workers were trapped, with no escape from the cruel and unforgiving world of Packingtown. As Sinclair so eloquently puts it, the consequences of this system were as inevitable and widespread as those under chattel slavery.

When authors write novels, they often use various techniques to evoke certain feelings or attitudes from their readers. These techniques can be quite effective, and F. Scott Fitzgerald is no exception. In his iconic novel The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald employs several of these techniques to shape the reader's perception of key subjects. One of these techniques is pairing an adjective and a noun in a way that doesn't typically mesh, to create an unexpected aura around the subject. Another technique is assigning meaning to a symbol, only to reuse it for the same purpose later on. Fitzgerald frequently uses the latter technique with colors, including gold, green, white, and various shades of pink and red. In The Great Gatsby, he gradually builds up connotations for certain colors, particularly white and gray, before utilizing them to convey a specific emotion or feeling associated with a pivotal object.

Fitzgerald develops the meaning of white and gray in the beginning of the novel, implying uniformity and a sense of sameness. White is portrayed as somewhat upscale and refined, while gray is depicted as more aged and faded. He initially establishes this meaning by consistently using these colors throughout the novel. For example, Daisy and Jordan are often seen wearing white, and even other characters like Nick wear white attire to Gatsby's parties. However, when Nick describes the party, he notes the use of "primary colors," which stands out from the predominantly white-and-gray aesthetic. Fitzgerald further reinforces this meaning by using these colors to describe mundane, unremarkable subjects, such as Nick's commute to work or the apartment buildings in the city. He also applies these colors to ordinary people or places, like Jordan and Daisy's "white girlhood" or the "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes.

After establishing the meaning of white and gray, Fitzgerald uses them to signify a lack of importance or uniformity in various subjects, starting with Daisy. After a period of relative scarcity of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as dressed in white in a "little white roadster," giving readers the impression that she is not a fully fleshed-out character, but rather a uniform, something that Gatsby desires but cannot attain. Fitzgerald employs this technique repeatedly to give the impression of Daisy as a more uniform, unremarkable figure, such as when he describes a "gray haze" around her fur collar or her wearing a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County boasts an incredibly productive agricultural sector, thanks to its pleasant, sunny climate. The region grows a wide variety of crops, including tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Interestingly, there's a significant demand for locally produced, organic community-supported agriculture food in the area, with numerous organizations experiencing lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many of these farms offer tours of their agricultural operations, as well as opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. By adopting organic farming practices, landowners can benefit from government programs while also protecting and enhancing local habitats, thus allowing for recreational use and educational opportunities.

While organic farming offers many benefits, including greater biodiversity due to the absence of chemicals in the soil and water, it often comes with higher costs. Organic farming requires more labor and management to control pests and weeds, fertilize the soil without chemicals, and mitigate losses, which can be greater than those experienced with conventional methods. Additionally, small organic farms are often less efficient than larger operations and may face higher labor costs for practices that benefit wildlife, such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species control, and managing plant growth to create specific conditions like edge habitats or open patches of ground.

The proposed land for this scenario is a 160-acre parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. The land features a mix of chaparral, non-native Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland, bordering the Cleveland National Forest. This area falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which currently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered or declining. These species include the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher.

This land has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries before being settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. The parcel was part of an original homestead patent, suggesting it was used for grazing and/or wood production for many years.

I selected a piece of property from a real estate website and researched government programs to determine the options available to a small farmer seeking to mitigate costs and preserve wildlife-friendly operations. As a model of what someone farming this land might attempt to achieve, I drew inspiration from an organic farm in the same area.

In any negotiation, understanding the role of culture is vital. However, culture is not a fixed entity that can be easily defined or stereotyped. It's more often a complex tapestry of nuances, where what culture is not can be just as telling as what it actually is. Broad statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" oversimplify the richness of a culture. Instead, a negotiator should focus on grasping the significance of a culture in the context of the negotiation, and how it will impact the discussion at hand.

When engaging with a foreign culture, we inevitably draw parallels to our own, often leading to misunderstandings. To navigate these differences, one must not only study a culture's history and prejudices but also be willing to accept it for what it is, rather than judging or trying to change it. This acceptance is especially crucial when dealing with a weaker bargaining position or negotiating in a foreign territory. Demonstrating respect for a culture's traditions and beliefs can be a powerful tool in bridging cultural divides and moving the negotiation forward.

Culture is not limited to national or international boundaries. Companies within a nation often develop their own unique corporate culture, characterized by distinct values, communication styles, and hiring practices. For instance, some companies prioritize long work hours, while others encourage a more relaxed schedule. Employee dress codes, communication styles, and philanthropic efforts can all reveal the underlying corporate culture. Even within the same nation, different companies and regions can exhibit vastly different corporate cultures.

Understanding a culture's values is equally crucial, as they provide the underlying motivations and driving forces. If a culture values saving face or communal harmony, a negotiator is unlikely to publicly embarrass their company or superior. On the other hand, a culture that places a high value on a hard-driven bargain may not be inclined to settle quickly. By considering these cultural nuances before the negotiation, a negotiator can gain a crucial edge. However, it's equally important to learn about the personal dynamics of the opposing party, as this can be the key to a successful negotiation.

It's often said, "There is no God," but this phrase is something that both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas strongly disagree with, as seen in their respective writings on the existence of God. Both of these thinkers present arguments in defense of the same concept of God, so in order to compare their theories, we'll assume they're correct in their belief in the God of the Bible. After all, comparing their arguments to a God figure that doesn't resemble the one they're defending wouldn't allow for a fair comparison.

When looking at their arguments, it's clear that neither of them provides a complete basis for believing in God. One of the main issues with their arguments is that they both miss the bigger picture. I think this point can be best understood by examining the basic arguments of each author in more detail.

St. Anselm's argument is based on the idea that we can find proof of God's existence within our own minds. He suggests that because we can't effectively conceive God's nonexistence, it's clear that he exists. While this idea may be a bit confusing at times, the basic gist is that the proof for God lies within our own understanding. This idea is often referred to as faith within Christian texts, and it's based on the idea that we don't need external evidence to prove the existence of God - just our own knowledge.

On the other hand, St. Thomas Aquinas has a very different approach. He believes that we can prove God's existence using reason and empirical evidence alone, with no need for faith. This idea would be useful in spreading the message of Christianity because it would allow new converts to be convinced through logic rather than faith. Aquinas presents five different logical arguments to support the existence of God, which include change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Essentially, he argues that the existence of God is a logical necessity - if you're missing one puzzle piece, you can still understand its features and existence without actually seeing it.

In the early days of recorded history, a prince was born, who would one day be known as the Buddha. As time passed, he abandoned his royal life and embarked on a spiritual journey that led to his enlightenment. His teachings eventually gave rise to Buddhism, with the Theravada sect being one of its most traditional forms. This ancient faith is over 2,500 years old, and it's undergone significant changes since the Buddha's time. For instance, in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, the annual water-cutting ceremony is an event that's deeply rooted in tradition, although the Buddha never mentioned it. This illustrates the extent to which the religion has evolved over time, from its superficial customs to its fundamental principles. As a result, the Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt its doctrine in response to both internal and external influences, some of which have been hostile and others benevolent.

Throughout this discussion, we'll be using certain key terms. An internal force is defined as a factor that arises from within the Buddhist community, regardless of whether its members are monks or laypeople. In contrast, an external force refers to any influence from outside the Buddhist community. A hostile force is any force that harms or seeks to damage the Buddhist community, often stemming from a negative perception of the faith. On the other hand, a benign force is one that doesn't aim to harm or help the community, but may inadvertently have either effect.

To begin with, it's essential to understand the core principles of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka, which is comprised of three baskets of Buddhist scripture. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka provides the metaphysical framework of Buddhism. This framework includes concepts such as Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering in life), and Anicca (the impermanence of everything). Only by recognizing these concepts can one break free from Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which continues endlessly. Along with Sansara, one's attachment to lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) will also cease when one becomes enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for laymen and monks alike, with five precepts for laymen (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances) and a more detailed set of disciplinary rules for monks. The most fundamental concept in Buddhism is the four noble truths: Dukkha, the truth that life is suffering; the attachment that causes suffering; the possibility of overcoming suffering; and the path to achieve that liberation.

The rivalry between the United States and Mexico is a prime example of a longstanding feud that spanned an impressive 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts, 2000, p. 145). The peak of this animosity was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the U.S. gained the upper hand and claimed Texas and the Southwest as its own territory. The tension between the two nations was fueled by numerous clashes, which eventually subsided just before the outbreak of World War I. The initial spark of this rivalry emerged from fundamental differences in their values, customs, and faith, along with significant disparities in their material interests (Schmitt, 1974, p. 30-31). 

This type of long-standing rivalry is not unique to the U.S. and Mexico; many nations bordering their neighbors often develop opposing interests, contributing to the formation of deep-seated rivalries. The U.S. and Mexico are not alone in their historical tensions with their neighboring countries; David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that Mexico and Cuba are the only two nations that have consistently posed significant diplomatic problems for the U.S. (p. 41). Both of these countries are geographically close to the U.S. and have historically vied for its attention, whereas many other Latin American nations have maintained more positive relationships with the U.S.

Religious differences played a significant role in the rift between the two nations, a common thread in the history of various international conflicts. Sally Frahm (2001) points out that, "if Americans opposed fascism and communism in the 20th century, they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries" (p. 86). In a similar vein, the ideological struggle between the U.S. and the Soviet Union during the Cold War was, in part, a clash over core values and vital interests. In the case of the U.S. and Mexico, however, the underlying conflict was rooted in their differing religious preferences, inherited from their colonial past. This inherent distrust was a major obstacle to establishing friendly diplomatic relations between the two nations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) documented 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during the 57-year rivalry period. The majority of these disputes revolved around territorial issues, including border raids and frontier problems. The problem of bandits and outlaws from American border towns further exacerbated tensions until both nations deployed military force along their borders (Schmitt, 1974, p. 97).

The rivalry between the two nations began to subside as "Mexico became increasingly reliant on the United States" (Schmitt, 1974, p. 109) and eventually ended as U.S. ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century (p. 110).

Fifteen years ago, my life took an unexpected turn when I suddenly fell ill with an illness I was previously unaware of. At the time, I was working as a nurse, a profession I had chosen for the stability and security it offered, especially given my tumultuous childhood. The constant reassurance was that "you'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." Thus, even though my true aspirations lay in science and journalism, I pursued nursing. 

However, fate had other plans. At 46, I was left with little savings, unable to work, and facing a future shrouded in uncertainty. Fifteen years of living off social security disability have left me with nothing to call my own. Each day is a struggle, a constant battle for security, safety, and self-esteem. Yet, amidst the chaos, one truth remains: I couldn't have navigated these difficult years without the unwavering support of my family and a handful of loyal friends. In times of true crisis, one's strength is often an illusion. 

My point is that life is unpredictable, and emergencies can strike at any moment, big or small. No matter how well-prepared one is, some challenges are too great to overcome alone. 

While I agree that the US needs to rethink its reliance on a faltering government, I firmly believe that a more effective solution lies in fostering a culture of mutual support and help among Americans. Rather than relying solely on the government, we should encourage people to trust and rely on one another. This approach would be a more effective safeguard against life's uncertainties. 

The notion of rugged individualism, often touted by American conservatives, is often romanticized. However, the true secret to the success of our forefathers was not their isolation but their compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast alone; they relied on each other for survival. 

So, by all means, be prepared. I have my own disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and other essentials. If you have the means, consider starting a small farm or acquiring a wood stove. But while you're at it, take the time to get to know your neighbors. Building a community that looks out for one another is the most effective way to navigate life's uncertainties.

Evolutionary changes in organisms have long been a subject of interest and debate among scientists. One question that has puzzled researchers for years is what drives the direction of evolutionary change. It's surprising that even today, despite the significant progress made in understanding organic forms, defining them in mathematical terms remains a daunting task. However, recent studies have applied mathematical modeling to various aspects of mollusk development, both during their growth and throughout their evolutionary history (Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our current research aims to explore how mathematical modeling, combined with experimental studies, can help explain the mechanisms behind the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change in Prunum. 

To achieve this, we employed X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify key parameters that can be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were then input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). By using these parameters, we created hypothetical shell morphologies that can help us understand the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. The results of our study are being integrated with experimental and descriptive research to gain a deeper understanding of macroevolutionary events in this group.

Considering a shell as a tube that moves through 360 degrees of space over time, we can break it down into distinct components. The revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are known as whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis, known as the columella, runs through the central column of the shell. The speed at which the whorls grow can vary, and a continuous line separating each whorl is called a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one, known as the body whorl. The spire consists of all the whorls except the last, while the apex is the tip of the spire and the base is the opposite end. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Studying shells involves examining them from various angles, including apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. Typically, shells are viewed from an apertural perspective, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.

A method for counting whorls involves first viewing the shell from the apical perspective and determining where the first suture begins. By drawing a line to divide the shell into two parts, we can then count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl. 

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal grows its shell. By tracing the path of the aperture, we can use coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture and the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture. This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented, allowing us to formulate a mathematical model of the mollusk's skeletogenesis. Once we have a mathematical formulation, we can then vary parameters to modify the mollusk's development.

For the past decade, Indonesia has seen little progress in reducing neonatal and infant mortality rates.  Despite making significant strides in achieving Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, the country still lags behind in improving child and maternal health indicators.  To understand the reasons behind these shortcomings, it's essential to examine the health system's weaknesses, rather than focusing solely on program-specific interventions.

One area of improvement has been the number of births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% now meeting this target.  However, this statistic includes traditional workers like midwives, who may not be equipped to handle complicated pregnancies and, as a result, contribute to high maternal mortality rates due to hemorrhage.  This achievement is somewhat misleading, highlighting the need for further action.  Furthermore, there's been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by a healthcare professional.  Data on postnatal care is incomplete, but it's clear that this area is a concern, with low rates across the country.

The cesarean-section rate in Indonesia remains unacceptably low at around 4%.  This rate is even more concerning when considering the significant disparity between urban and rural areas, with a 5% difference between the two.  This disparity is a clear indication of unequal access to healthcare services, with a focus on urban areas.  Another issue is the lack of vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles.  It's clear that the poor face significant challenges in accessing healthcare services, largely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the primary question is how to effectively address the lack of service.  Should Indonesia focus on developing program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system, prioritizing the well-being of mothers and children before and after pregnancy?  While programmatic approaches may seem appealing due to their targeted objectives and potential for faster results, there are significant drawbacks to consider.  One major concern is that investing heavily in one area can lead to a lack of funding and resources for other critical areas, causing a brain drain of skilled healthcare workers.  Additionally, running multiple parallel programs for the same area can result in duplication of services, increased paperwork, and inefficiencies.

Victorian novels are often associated with their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the time period.  However, two novels that stand out from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  Both of these novels incorporate elements of mystery and a touch of the bizarre, which deviates from the typical characteristics of the era.  This unique approach enhances the characters within each work, offering a deeper look into their thoughts and emotions.

As Oliver Twist delves into the darker side of the period, the author skillfully weaves together a complex web of thoughts and events.  The main character's mind is flooded with jumbled ideas, making it difficult for him to distinguish reality from fantasy.  In one particular instance, Oliver finds himself walking between Sikes and Crackit, who are engaged in a heated argument.  The words they speak seem to echo in his mind, and when he regains his composure, he realizes that he's having a conversation with them.  Suddenly, the sound of gunfire shatters the atmosphere, and Oliver is swept away by an unseen force.  Throughout this chaotic scene, Oliver experiences a nagging sense of pain, which haunts him relentlessly.

Both novels use dream sequences or dreamlike states to convey this sense of mystery, although the content and purpose vary between the two.  Oliver Twist often employs these strange occurrences to reveal Oliver's inner turmoil, his deep-seated fears, and his perception of the world around him.  When Oliver relives the shooting scene in chapter 28, he does so in a state of vivid imagination, as if it's a recurring nightmare.  This passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over the events that unfold, as well as the dire state of his health, which is reflected in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit.  The shooting overwhelms Oliver, numbing his senses as he's whisked away by an unseen force.  He's forced to relive his despair, his pain now constant and linked to fear rather than surprise.  This scene raises questions about whose will led to his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own.  Oliver's growing sense of defeat is also implied, as if Fagin's influence has broken him, forcing him to accept this despair and rendering him unable to react.

In Wuthering Heights, the author similarly employs dreamlike states to convey the turmoil and mystery of the characters.  The passage describes the passage of time as a perpetual state of limbo, with days blurring together and nights feeling both long and fleeting.  This sense of timelessness reflects the characters' own emotional states, which are characterized by a sense of desperation and longing.

A couple of years ago, I worked at an after-school program where I tutored elementary age students in various subjects. My strengths were in English and reading, and I was assigned to help a boy named Adrian, who was struggling with reading. As I worked with him, I realized that something was amiss - he had an unusual problem with reading. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others were way off. It was quite peculiar. Adrian's parents were of Latino descent, but he spoke perfect English, which only added to the confusion. We made little progress until I met his mother, who only spoke Spanish. With my limited Spanish skills, we managed to communicate, and it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read just fine, but he just didn't know the English alphabet well. I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the problem of the language barrier in schools, particularly in California. It's not always as obvious as we think, and even a child who speaks perfect English can still struggle with reading. Everyone agrees that this problem exists, so what's the solution? In Adrian's case, tutoring in English reading, especially the alphabet and pronunciations, was relatively straightforward. However, for children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes - none of these alone will fix the problem. The key lies in combining them all.

The dual language system is an excellent idea, not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. Studies have shown that children in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. Many fear that this approach is a waste of resources, but that's a misconception. If we were to implement these programs as the norm, rather than the exception, all children would benefit from them. So, how do we do it? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? That's unrealistic. Instead, we could have special aids, tutors, or whatever you call them, who are bilingual.

For most of us, the concept of something greater than ourselves has been instilled in us since childhood. We've been taught about it in Sunday school, at Temple, or in our own introspection. Some of us accept the faith passed down to us from our parents, while others reject it entirely, believing that there's no truth beyond our own personal perspectives. We might switch between different value systems, searching for a guiding light in the darkness. This search for meaning helps us define ourselves and find our own unique sense of spirituality.

I recall a conversation with my dad, where he revealed his favorite type of bird – the cardinal.  We sat on our porch, listening to the rain, the smell of our cigarettes lingering in the air. The sound of the rainwater rushing through the gutters and drowning the nearby plants created a melancholic atmosphere. My dad's appearance had changed in recent months; he'd lost weight, and his hair had thinned out. He stared into the rain, lost in thought, avoiding eye contact. I felt a mix of emotions – loneliness, fear, and the inability to talk to him about his impending passing. I hugged him, sat back down, and joined him in gazing out into the rain, trying to cherish the moment.

My dad passed away in December, just five days after my 22nd birthday. The chemo and radiation had prolonged his life, but not alleviated his suffering. I couldn't understand the purpose of prolonging his suffering. I stopped praying, wondering if God had stopped listening to me long ago. If there was a God, I thought, he must have stopped caring about me.

I didn't want to witness my father's final moments, so I chose not to be there. I wanted to remember him for the life he lived, not the way he died. I knew my dad better than anyone, and I believed he wouldn't have wanted me to be a spectator to his passing. I spent three days curled up in bed, waiting for the news. But no one even bothered to call me.

The term "Gothic Novel" is an intriguing oxymoron that encapsulates the essence of something both old and new.  As Ian Watt so eloquently puts it, "Gothic Novel" is, in essence, 'Old-New.' The Gothic mode has been met with both praise and criticism, with some viewing it as lacking depth and others admiring its ability to evoke the 'terrible sublime' (Burke).  In creating the first "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto skillfully blended elements of both the old and modern romance genres, forging a new literary path. Walpole cleverly combined ancient theatrical elements and modern novelistic mimicry to craft a story he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). This novel drew heavily from medieval theatrical traditions, architecture, and customs, which were seen as outdated and unsophisticated in comparison to the modern world. The fusion of these elements with the novel's format, which allowed readers a more personal glimpse into the characters' psychology, is what has allowed the Gothic genre to endure and maintain its relevance across time, becoming both obsolete and new to readers from different eras.

One of the central themes in Gothic literature is the concept of chivalry, which originated in the medieval era. The original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto, retains and reinterprets this concept, elevating it to an idealized state. Chivalry represented the epitome of the noble knight: brave, honorable, and competent. Gothic writers, including Walpole, were drawn to this ideal and saw it as a benchmark for the present society, which they perceived as lacking. By employing chivalric concepts and mannerisms, the "gothic past" was romanticized and idealized, foreshadowing the evolution of Gothic to Romanticism. This is exemplified in characters like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits, including being a prince, having suffered through tragedy, and being mistakenly believed to have been killed by infidels. Frederic's description is replete with traditional chivalric imagery, which is later exaggerated, introducing the trope of excess that would become a hallmark of the Gothic genre (66).

Supply chain management is the intricate process of moving goods from the initial customer order to the final stage of distribution, encompassing the raw materials, production, and delivery to the customer. This concept was first coined in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant who described the entire process of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to satisfy customers' needs in a timely and efficient manner. At the heart of supply chain management are six fundamental elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. By mastering these elements, business managers can provide top-notch customer service.

Production is the foundation upon which the entire supply chain process is built. It involves determining the when, why, where, and how of production, including understanding customer demands. To grasp customer needs, managers examine market trends, which serve as the largest indicator of customer demands. Once market analysis is complete, managers decide what products to produce, in what quantities, and where to produce them, taking into account customer satisfaction and demand. Scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment are also crucial tasks at this stage. As I've witnessed firsthand in my past experience working at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores, having a well-defined process and layout is essential for smooth operations and prevents confusion and misdirection.

Supply, the second key element, involves making strategic decisions about the core capabilities of a facility and outsourcing partnerships. A company may have multiple divisions for a single product, each with its unique equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must choose the most suitable division for each process or decide to outsource work to other companies to enhance velocity – the ability to deliver quality, flexibility, and cost-effectiveness. By streamlining operations through outsourcing, companies can reduce costs and maintain a competitive edge.

I recently came across a disturbing message scrawled on a street corner in Burma, a country ruled by a ruthless military junta that seized power in 1962 through a violent coup. The sign held by Ellen Page, star of the critically acclaimed film Juno, reads "Hitler is alive in Burma", a haunting reference to the country's history of oppression and human rights abuses. Burma, also known as Myanmar, has been plagued by protests and violence, including the infamous "Saffron Revolution" of 2007, led by Buddhist monks who were met with brutal suppression by the military.

The situation in Burma is just one example of a long history of governments trying to silence dissent and maintain control over their citizens. Throughout history, rulers have claimed divine right to absolute power, from early Roman emperors to Japanese emperors who were believed to be gods. Even in modern times, some leaders have used their positions to silence critics and opponents. For instance, President George W. Bush has been known to consult with Ted Haggard, the head of a conservative Christian group, on a regular basis.

There have been numerous examples of brutal suppression of dissent throughout history. The 1989 Tiananmen Square protests in China, where students and intellectuals demanded an end to authoritarian rule, resulted in a reported death toll of between 200 and 3,000 people. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, in which Hutu militias and the government killed an estimated 800,000 people, is another extreme example of state-sponsored violence. The Nazi regime's systematic persecution and murder of Jews and other minority groups during World War II is a stark reminder of the dangers of unchecked power and hatred.

Duke Ellington left a lasting impact on jazz primarily due to his extended career and his exceptional ability to shape his orchestra. While his piano presence is subtle in many of the compositions featured in this assignment, as a composer Ellington excelled in crafting rich and complex pieces that showcased the unique talents of each band member. He developed the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing intricately orchestrated sections that highlighted the distinct styles of individual band members. By doing so, Ellington also emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, creating cohesive and original sounds to suit each piece. His mastery of each player's sound and how they interacted within the growing ensemble allowed him to create some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative approach to sound and voice in his work, particularly in Creole Love Call, where he uses voice as a jazz instrument throughout his career. This early example demonstrates Ellington's ability to enhance texture and color without the restrictions of lyrics. Creole Love Call, a slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece, features six distinct choruses that showcase Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists. The piece's structure is as follows:

Chorus 1: A call-and-response exchange between voice and reeds, starting with a smooth and melodic voice that transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with a call-and-response between the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, where the reeds initiate the call-and-response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call-and-response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice takes on the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add tone color to this piece is just one example of a stylistic trait that runs throughout his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call-and-response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing creates a rich and complementary sound by blending the vocal elements of Miley's playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

There was this persistent feeling inside of her that never seemed to be satisfied. It started when she was 14, as she was navigating the ups and downs of being a teenager. Three years later, at 17, she was still trying to make sense of it. She had come to the realization that she wanted someone rather than something, but nothing seemed to spark her interest in the guys around her. She often found herself pondering this strange phenomenon, trying to figure out what could be causing it. Theories had crossed her mind, but none of them seemed quite right.

For the most part, life at home was pretty laid-back. Her parents were easy-going and never argued with each other. They rarely argued with her either, except when she pushed her boundaries and asserted her independence. It was a trait that actually made her quite likable, given her friendly and outgoing personality.

But today was a different story. As she wandered from room to room, searching for inspiration, she was startled by a faint scream from the kitchen and her mother's distressed voice. Her heart racing, she rushed into the room, asking "Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother lying on the ground, wincing in pain. Her daughter quickly went to her side and put a supportive hand on her, trying to help. "Ow... sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital," her mother managed to say between deep breaths. The daughter sprang into action, helping her mother to the car and getting her comfortable in the backseat.

The hospital was a whirlwind of disinfectant and anxiety, but she was so focused on her mother's well-being that she didn't register the fear. She rushed her mother inside and called for medical help. A team of worried faces gathered around, and they quickly got her mother onto a rolling bed and whisked her away for immediate attention. Her daughter was left sitting anxiously, waiting for news.

It turned out her mother had taken a tumble off a stepping stool while trying to grab a vase from a high cabinet.

The purpose of this study was to investigate the relationship between adhering to the "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) and the risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke mortality. The study found that a "modified Med diet score" (aMed score), which emphasizes the consumption of plant-based foods, healthy fats, and fish, is associated with a reduced risk of CHD and stroke. This modified Med diet is characterized by higher intake of fruits, nuts, whole grains, legumes, monounsaturated fats, and fish, and lower intake of animal products and saturated fats, with moderate alcohol consumption allowed.

Previous studies have shown that a Med diet is linked to a lower risk of total and cardiovascular mortality, and that it's more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and improving cholesterol levels in obese individuals. However, these studies didn't specifically examine the relationship between the Med diet and stroke or stroke mortality.

This study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of heart disease or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a large cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six periods from 1984 to 2004, the researchers calculated the aMed diet score using questionnaires that asked participants about their nutrient intake over the past year. Almost all participants continued to participate throughout the 20-year study period.

The researchers validated the accuracy of the questionnaires and confirmed reports of heart disease, stroke, and other health outcomes through medical records, hospital records, autopsy reports, or death certificates. In cases where records were not available, the researchers classified the cases as "probable," which accounted for about 17% of all strokes and 24% of non-fatal heart attacks.

To account for individual variations in diet and better represent long-term dietary habits, the researchers averaged the aMed scores from multiple questionnaires over time. They also adjusted for potential confounders, such as age, smoking status, body mass index, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using a statistical model, the researchers found that a higher aMed score was associated with a lower risk of CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up period, 2391 cases of CHD, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths were reported. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile.

In 2007, the United States experienced a devastating economic downturn. High unemployment rates, a collapsing housing market, and the downfall of top corporations left many wondering how this financial disaster occurred and how it can be prevented. To put it simply, the crisis was born from reckless and uninformed political decisions that pressured banks and companies to issue sub-prime loans into a fragile financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were forced to take on and repackage these mortgages into complex financial instruments, only to see the entire economy suffer when borrowers defaulted on these loans. The chaos then spread to the repackaged mortgages and, ultimately, the rest of the economy.

The roots of this financial disaster date back to the late 1990s, during the Clinton administration. President Clinton sought to bolster his popularity by relaxing lending restrictions, which ultimately created the perfect storm for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. As reported by Steven Holmes of the New York Times in 1999, Fannie Mae, the country's largest mortgage underwriter, was under pressure from the administration to expand mortgage loans to low- and moderate-income individuals, while also meeting the expectations of its shareholders. Holmes accurately predicted the consequences of these actions: "But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As previously discussed, the reckless lending practices would inevitably lead to a catastrophic economic collapse.
 
A combination of factors contributed to the economic downturn, one of which was the complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely used in the years leading up to the crisis, intertwining various sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led U.S. households and financial markets to become heavily invested in the housing market, leaving them vulnerable to even slight price changes. 
When the housing bubble burst, the financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities were severely affected. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively held $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, accounting for about 30% of the country's GDP. Ultimately, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at a low price, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were taken over by the government in September 2008.

Ah, the infamous exposition - that section of your story where your writing skills are put to the test, leaving readers either in awe or nodding off in their chairs. Dr. Merlin has been known to frantically click the 'undo' button more than once when she finds herself drowning in a sea of unnecessary details. Exposition, it seems, is not exactly a welcome guest in the world of storytelling.

As writers, we've all been warned about the perils of "telling, not showing," but Dr. Merlin still succumbs to lengthy descriptions of backstories, often leaving readers wondering when the real story will begin. Exposition is the pesky critic on your shoulder, urging you to provide context at the expense of actual plot progression. It's the voice that whispers, "Get the history out of the way so we can get to the good stuff."

In fiction, exposition is when an author chooses to tell the reader what's happening, rather than show it through action, dialogue, or sensory details. In film, it's often manifested as a character dumping a wealth of information on another character, usually in a clunky and info-dumpy way. Think of it as a literary equivalent of a "core dump" a la "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."

Take, for instance, a story where the protagonist's love interest is introduced with a grandiose passage detailing their entire history: where they met, how they married, and the tragic circumstances of their partner's demise. It's unlikely that this lengthy exposition would unfold over two pages, with the couple barely exchanging a few lines of dialogue. Instead, a skilled author would weave a more nuanced introduction, gradually revealing the husband's character through their speech, mannerisms, and interactions. This would not only make the reader invested in their fate but also provide valuable insight into the protagonist's personality, values, and motivations.

By adding depth and context to the bare-bones narrative, you create an emotionally resonant connection between the reader and the characters. In short, you'd expect the story to deliver more than just the skeletal outline: "They met, they married, he died." A good writer knows that there's no substitute for rich, sensory details that breathe life into the narrative.

So, the next time you find yourself tempted to skim over the surface-level details, remember that a good story is built on more than just exposition. Provide the meat, not just the bones.

I recently watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio, which left me thinking about the way news is presented. The first one I tuned into was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). They had a breaking story about a man in Ashley, Ohio, who stabbed his wife. The man's name was Shad Hostettler, and the news team devoted a reasonable two minutes to the developing story, stating that he had stabbed her multiple times and been arrested. I believe this was an adequate amount of coverage for the circumstances.

The second story that caught my attention was about an early morning shooting of an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, and no arrests had been made at the time. The SWAT team was investigating the crime, but this story seemed to be glossed over. I've noticed a pattern where minorities are often underreported when they're victims of a crime. In contrast, when a white person is a victim, the media tends to go into overdrive, whereas if it's a minority person, they're lucky if it even gets mentioned.

The news team then moved on to a story about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They shared details about the location where the incident occurred and stated that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers were offering a $5,000 reward for tips that could lead to the shooter's arrest.

The forecast for the weekend was also covered, with predictions of rain and thunderstorms on Saturday afternoon. Temperatures were expected to remain in the mid to low eighties, but the segment was a bit too brief and seemed like a teaser to keep viewers hooked.

Another story they ran with was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The perpetrator was described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt, approximately six feet tall, and weighing around 150 pounds. I found it striking that they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his skin color and how dark he was.

Lastly, they covered a story about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin who was found guilty of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana to Ohio from Texas. What caught my attention was that instead of stating the sentence as 25 years in prison, they mentioned "300 months," which seemed unnecessary and possibly an attempt to make the sentence sound harsher. Additionally, they mentioned that he was a Hispanic man, which I didn't think was particularly relevant to the story.

In the intricate web of human relationships, the bond between brothers stands out as an unbreakable and complex connection. This unique tie is woven with various emotions - love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty - making it hard to unravel. Brothers have a deep understanding of each other that goes beyond the realm of ordinary relationships, and when they look at their brothers, they see a reflection of themselves. It's during intense moments that the true nature of their bond reveals itself, whether it's a beautiful or a destructive one. These emotions come with a cost, and dealing with their consequences is an integral part of understanding the bond. When one brother looks into another and sees their own reflection staring back, they gain insight into their own character through their actions and the repercussions that follow.

In James Hurst's "The Scarlet Ibis," this theme is expertly explored, along with the cluster of emotions that come with it. Against the backdrop of a rich, vivid landscape, two brothers embark on a doomed journey, where bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in a heart-wrenching climax. Only one brother manages to escape alive. The theme is skillfully conveyed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as the narrator's perspective, which highlights the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and their perception of the world around them. Both of these greatly influence their actions.

At the core of the protagonist's behavior lies a single, driving emotion: pride. From their initial outings together until their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He had envisioned a brother who could learn from him and share in his adventures, like "holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp." He wanted a companion to join him in racing to Horsehead Landing and perching in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn. However, Doodle's fragile health made these dreams seem impossible. Born with a weak heart, Doodle's prospects for survival, let alone participating in physically demanding activities, were slim to none. The young protagonist's fantasies were shattered in an instant, leaving him with a deep sense of disappointment and frustration. He even grapples with anger towards his brother, as revealed by his recollection of contemplating suffocating him with a pillow. Yet, his heart softens when Doodle smiles at him, revealing a glimmer of hope. This moment showcases the protagonist's innate love for his brother, which he had likely been hiding beneath his pride and anger.

The human brain is a complex and innovative system that processes information in a multitude of ways. Over the years, our understanding of the brain has advanced, and so have the metaphors used to describe it. Initially, we thought of the brain like a simple wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and more recently, a computer. However, it's essential to remember that these metaphors are limited and can lead to oversimplification and incorrect conclusions.

The process of information processing starts when our sensory organs transform physical stimuli, such as touch, heat, sound, or light, into electrical signals. This sensory information is then repeatedly processed by the brain using both bottom-up and top-down approaches. For instance, when looking at a black box on a white background, the brain's bottom-up processing puts together basic information like color, orientation, and object borders to identify the box. Top-down processing then speeds up recognition by using the decisions made during bottom-up processing. It might help you identify the object as a black box instead of a hole in the background.

As information is processed to a certain level, an attention filter decides its importance and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when looking down, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually, but you might pick out your name in a noisy room. There are various stages of processing, and the results are constantly modulated by attention.

For the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term memory. Information is encoded in various ways specific to each type of sensory stimulus. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, phonemically, or semantically, depending on its appearance, sound, or meaning. Once stored, information must be maintained. Research suggests that working memory, which stores information for around 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a series of neurons for a short period. Long-term memory is thought to be maintained through the structure of certain proteins.

There are various models describing how knowledge is organized in the brain, each based on different approaches like human memory retrieval, computer science, or neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes that there are nodes representing concepts and that these nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For instance, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so forth.

In his thought-provoking novel, Brave New World, Aldous Huxley issues a stark warning about the dangers of unchecked technological advancements and the capitalistic systems that drive them. He creates a dystopian society where people value community over individuality and are conditioned to prioritize immediate gratification above all else. The citizens are mere pawns in a larger game, confined to a narrow ideology dictated by the World Controller. Through a Marxist lens, one can see Huxley's underlying concerns about the development of these systems, which eerily foreshadow the emerging economy of his time.

Huxley uses Marxist concepts to satirize capitalism, highlighting the idea of false consciousness. In this context, the common citizenry is kept in the dark about their true relationships with other social classes, too focused on their own self-interest to grasp the bigger picture. This is achieved through the ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, as evident in the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The lower classes, represented by Deltas and Gammas, are devoid of autonomy, with their drive to consume, spend, and indulge amplified through hypnopædia. The World Controller masterfully manipulates this desire, showcasing a clear example of hegemony, where a dominant group (the upper classes) exercises control over the others. The lower classes are oblivious to this manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that reinforces the existing social structure. Meanwhile, the upper classes, represented by Alphas and Betas, are aware of the manipulation but choose to accept their position, with few exceptions like Bernard.

In this world, meaningful relationships between individuals are non-existent. Characters are one-dimensional, lacking depth, which may suggest that the rise of technology and capitalism together rob people of their free will and emotional expression. Love and intense emotions are absent, replaced by superficial interactions, often reduced to shallow comments about physical appearance. The complacency of each social class within the hierarchy is a testament to the socioeconomic effects of capitalism, where individuals are convinced of their superiority as long as they conform to the norms of their peers.

As a student at University Park for over two and a half years now, I've experienced the challenges of navigating campus. For many of us, including myself, getting around campus can be a real issue. My freshman year, I was assigned to an East Halls dorm, which is situated on the far eastern edge of campus – excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. The commute from Stuart Hall, my hometown on campus, to classes in the Willard building, near the heart of campus, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when the weather is bad. I recently spoke to a fellow alumnus who's not much older than me, and they shared that not too long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by vast tracts of unused land. Today, that empty space has been transformed into sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and the health services building, and surrounding apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. In my opinion, the best solution to this problem is the bicycle. However, having a bike is only half the battle – students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be designed with the needs of bicyclists in mind.

I had a conversation with a friend who recently took up bicycling again after a few-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped cycling in the first place. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Not only is bicycling good for your physical health, but it's also the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical exertion can take you 30 miles or more. As an off-campus resident, I'm just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was buying a bike. With my classes in Thomas building, a 25-minute walk from my home, I can cut that time down to just 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only catch is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to navigate, whether I'm on a bike or on foot. While walking has its merits, I'm just too busy to do it. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class, and it would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That's over two and a half hours every week – time I just can't afford to spare.
